
## Deep isolation findings (2026-07-24)
- STATIC mask geometry is CORRECT: with offset=in (write-on off) + frozen position/scale, FCP and
  engine both ~26% coverage, similar bbox. So parse/rasterize/feather/scale of a single static quad
  is fine. The bug is NOT static geometry.
- The divergence is ENTIRELY the WRITE-ON sweep. Engine coverage caps ~71-85% and HOLDS; FCP reaches
  100% by scene t~0.65 then conceals L->R at the very end (t>0.95).
- The mask legitimately animates Position (X -1045.8->2105.2, Y -2129->1870 over local 0.30->1.07)
  AND Scale (X const 2.088; Y 0.686->5.941 over local -0.20->0.57). Both are sampled by the write-on.
- The offset re-anchor (curveTime = timeSec - offset(0.30)) is NOT the cause: disabling it
  (FCT_NO_REANCHOR probe) leaves coverage at 71%.
- Write-on sub-time dump at t=0.70 (curveTime=0.494): the 13 swept quads run pos (-367,-1183)->(843,210),
  scale.Y 1.82->4.81. Early quads sit ABOVE the frame (Y=-1183, frame top -540); only late quads enter.
  The union traces a diagonal band that misses the frame's TOP-RIGHT and BOTTOM-LEFT corners.
- OPEN QUESTION for next iteration: why does FCP's swept mask reach 100% when the quad-union caps at
  ~71-85%? Hypotheses to test: (a) FCP's Scale.Y (up to 5.94) makes the quad tall enough to cover the
  full column at each X — check if the engine is applying the FULL scale.Y at the correct sub-times or
  clamping it; (b) the Scale curve local times [-0.20,0.57] vs Position [0.30,1.07] are on DIFFERENT
  anchors — the engine samples both at the same `st`, but FCP may co-evaluate them at a consistent
  scene time, so the engine's quad is smaller-than-FCP at the sweep positions where it matters;
  (c) FCP's reveal may be a continuous swept-region (not K=12 discrete quads) — increase K and/or
  rasterize the swept HULL between consecutive sub-quads to fill gaps.
- NEXT CONCRETE STEP: freeze Position to a static mid-frame value but KEEP Scale animating (and vice
  versa) to determine whether the coverage shortfall is driven by the Position sweep or the Scale ramp.

## ROOT CAUSE FOUND (2026-07-24) — anchor point is scaled, shifting the mask off-frame
Instrumented the mask's world transform (FCT_MTX_DEBUG) on the max-scale-static-centered repro:
  worldTransform: sx=1.846 (=2.088 mask × 0.884 parent ✓), sy=5.253, tx=1141, ty=1275 (!!)
The SCALE is correct, but the TRANSLATION is +1141,+1275 — WAY off the bottom-right of the 1920×1080
frame — even though the mask Position is (0,0). Source: the mask has Anchor Point Y=-238.4, and
buildTransformMatrix composes M = T(pos)·R·S·T(-anchor), i.e. screen = pos + S·(v - anchor). With
scaleY=5.253 and anchorY=-238, the anchor offset is SCALED: 238×5.253 ≈ 1250 = the ty shift. So the
whole mask is pushed off-frame, covering only 55% (static) / 71% (swept) instead of FCP's 94-100%.
CONTROL: FCP with anchorY=-238 → 94% coverage; anchorY=0 → 100%. So FCP applies the anchor but its
effect is SMALL (a slight shift), NOT the massive scaled shift the engine produces. => FCP does NOT
scale the anchor offset the way the engine does (or pivots scale around the anchor so the anchor
point stays fixed). This is the ROOT CAUSE of the Wipes__Diagonal mask-coverage divergence.

FIX DIRECTION (careful — buildTransformMatrix is shared by ALL 65 transitions; must not regress):
the anchor-point/scale composition needs to match Motion's convention. Candidates to test:
  (a) pivot-around-anchor: screen = pos + anchor + R·S·(v - anchor)  [anchor added back so the
      anchor point maps to pos+anchor, not scaled away] — verify against a layer that uses BOTH a
      non-zero anchor and scale (this mask) AND ones that currently pass (Fall anchor -540, Reflection
      anchor Z=960) so no regression.
  (b) anchor is a pure rotation pivot (not scaled/translated for scale) — Motion's "Anchor Point"
      may only pivot rotation, with scale about the layer origin.
  NEXT: read Motion's actual transform order (ENGINE_RE_PLAYBOOK / OZTransformNode) or empirically
  fit by rendering FCP with a few (anchor, scale) combos and matching the engine. Then implement +
  verify: this repro reaches ~99 dB, golden test:node green, min-regress no worse, full 65 re-scored.

## ROOT CAUSE FOUND (2026-07-24): anchor-point offset is SCALED by the layer scale (engine bug)
Isolated to a STATIC single frame: max Scale (X=2.088, Y=5.941) + Position (0,0), mask offset=in
(no write-on). FCP covers 94% (full frame, centered); engine covers 55% (bbox x[472,1726], shifted).
Instrumented the world transform passed to rasterizeShape: sx=1.846 (=2.088*0.884 parent, CORRECT),
sy=5.253, but **tx=1141, ty=1275** — the mask is translated OFF the bottom-right corner!
  - anchorY = -238.4; buildTransformMatrix uses M = T(pos)·R·S·T(-anchor), so a vertex maps to
    pos + S·(v - anchor). With pos=0, scaleY=5.253, anchorY=-238: the shape shifts by
    S·(-anchorY) = 5.253 * 238 ≈ +1250 in Y (== the observed ty=1275). The anchor offset is
    MAGNIFIED by the scale, pushing the mask off-frame.
  - FCP does NOT do this: FCP anchorY=-238 → 94% coverage, anchorY=0 → 100% (a SMALL shift), i.e.
    FCP's anchor effect is ~unscaled, keeping the shape centered. The engine scales it by 5.25×.
CONCLUSION: the divergence (coverage cap 55-71%, and the write-on "never reaches 100%") is because
the mask is shifted off-frame by the scaled anchor. Fix = correct the anchor/scale pivot composition
so a scaled layer pivots AROUND its anchor without a scaled translation (Motion's actual convention),
matching FCP. MUST verify against all other transitions that use anchor+scale (Movements 3D-fold
family, Replicator panels) — this is a core transform change, regress-check the full min-gate + a
broad slug re-score before shipping. This supersedes the earlier "write-on union caps 71%" framing:
the write-on is fine; the per-sub-time transform mis-scales the anchor.

## Anchor/scale convention probe (2026-07-24) — FCP behavior measured
Parent 'Transition Diagonal' scale stripped to 1; mask Position/Scale/Anchor set explicitly; measured
FCP coverage-bbox center (noisy — feathered partial shape, but indicative):
  sc=1 anchorY=0   -> yc 565 (shape natural centroid, cov 47%)
  sc=1 anchorY=200 -> yc 540 (cov 60%)
  sc=1 anchorY=-300-> yc 670 (cov 26%)
  sc=2 anchorY=0   -> yc 540 (cov 83%)
  sc=2 anchorY=200 -> yc 540 (cov 98%)  <- center INVARIANT to anchor at sc=2
  pos=(800,400) sc=1 -> EMPTY (Position DOES translate)
Neither 'pos+S(v-anchor)' nor 'pos+S(v-anchor)+anchor' cleanly fits the noisy bbox-center data.
The ENGINE currently over-shifts (anchor scaled by S -> +1250px off-frame at sc=5.25). NEXT: measure
with a SMALL UNFEATHERED shape + alpha centroid (not bbox) for a clean fit; derive the exact Motion
anchor/scale/position order; then fix buildTransformMatrix and regress-check all 65. Probe harness:
/tmp/mkmask.py (set pos/scale/anchor), /tmp/stripparent.py, /tmp/hrender.py (headless w/ DYLD reexec).
NOTE: headless worker segfaults intermittently on rapid repeated cold boots — re-run singly if a
frame is missing.

## Anchor convention probe (2026-07-24) — decode in progress
FCP mask transform behavior (parent scale stripped to 1, single static mask, coverage-bbox centroid;
NOTE: feathered asymmetric shape makes bbox-centroid NOISY — need a clean unfeathered small-quad +
alpha-weighted centroid for an exact fit):
  sc=1 pos=0 anchorY=0    -> yc 565 (shape's own centroid, cov 47%)
  sc=1 pos=0 anchorY=200  -> yc 540 (cov 60%)
  sc=1 pos=0 anchorY=-300 -> yc 670 (cov 26%)
  sc=1 pos=(800,400)      -> EMPTY (Position DOES translate, unscaled)
  sc=2 pos=0 anchorY=0    -> yc 540 cov 83%   (bbox saturates when shape is large)
  sc=2 pos=0 anchorY=200  -> yc 540 cov 98%   (anchor changes COVERAGE but not center at sc=2)
  sc=3 pos=0 anchorY=0    -> cov 99%
KEY: the ENGINE currently maps screen = pos + S·(v − anchor), which SCALES the anchor offset
(anchorY=-238 × scaleY=5.25 ≈ 1250px off-frame). FCP's anchor has a much SMALLER effect and does
NOT scale off-frame. The engine's buildTransformMatrix M = T(pos)·R·S·T(-anchor) is the suspect.
NEXT: (1) build a clean probe: replace the mask geometry with a SMALL UNFEATHERED square at known
coords, vary (pos, scale, anchor), measure alpha-weighted centroid (not bbox) — fit the exact
Motion formula. (2) Likely fix: pivot-around-anchor screen = pos + anchor·(1−S)... derive exactly.
(3) Apply to buildTransformMatrix; verify Wipes__Diagonal reaches ~99dB AND min-regress + full-65
re-score show NO regression (this fn is shared by every transition — Fall/Reflection/Rotate use
non-zero anchors + scale/rotation and currently pass, so the fix must preserve them).
Probe harness saved: /tmp/mkmask.py, /tmp/stripparent.py, /tmp/hrender.py.

## Anchor convention probe data (2026-07-24) — FCP, parent-scale stripped to 1
Probe harness: /tmp/mkmask.py (set pos/scale/anchor), /tmp/stripparent.py, /tmp/hrender.py.
  sc=1 pos=0 anchorY=0    -> yc 565 (shape natural centroid), cov 47%
  sc=1 pos=0 anchorY=200  -> yc 540, cov 60%
  sc=1 pos=0 anchorY=-300 -> yc 670, cov 26%
  sc=1 pos=(800,400)      -> EMPTY (Position translates the shape off-frame)
  sc=2 pos=0 anchorY=0    -> yc 540, cov 83%
  sc=2 pos=0 anchorY=200  -> yc 540, cov 98%  (center unchanged by anchor at sc=2)
  sc=3 pos=0 anchorY=0    -> yc 540, cov 99%
FINDINGS: (1) Position translates the shape (unscaled). (2) Scale scales the shape and its coverage
grows with scale. (3) Anchor's effect on the CENTER is SMALL and roughly scale-independent — NOT the
large scaleY×anchorY shift the engine applies. So FCP's anchor/scale composition keeps the shape
near-centered; the engine's M=T(pos)·S·T(-anchor) scales the anchor offset (238×5.25≈1250px) and
throws the mask off-frame. NEXT (implement in buildTransformMatrix, verify no 65-slug regression):
match FCP's convention — the anchor must not produce a scale-magnified translation for the mask.
Read the exact Motion order from the binary if the empirical fit stays ambiguous. Segfaults on rapid
repeated headless boots are benign (re-run singly).

## Clean square-probe (2026-07-24) — reveals a ~1.77x base scale + offset in the mask chain
Replaced the mask geometry with a sharp ±100 unfeathered SQUARE, feather=0, pos=(0,0) sc=1 anchor=0
(parent 'Transition Diagonal' scale stripped to 1). Expected: a 200×200 px square centered at world
(0,0). FCP RENDERS: 354×322 px at world centroid (250,-392). So even at "identity" mask transform,
a ~1.77× scale (354/200) AND an offset (+250,-392) are applied. Sources to check next iteration:
  - the "Gradient and background" GROUP transform (Position X=-248,Y=-435 — matches the ~-392 y offset
    roughly) is still in the chain (I only stripped the 'Transition Diagonal' layer scale, not the group).
  - a project-unit → pixel base scale (~1.77?) or the shape's Aspect Ratio (1.5) / Preserve Scale.
  - the mask Anchor Point Y=-238 default (I set it to 0 in the probe, but the group offset remains).
So the ~1.77× and offset are from the PARENT GROUP + possibly a project scale, NOT purely the mask.
NEXT: strip the group offset too, and add a known project scale, to get a clean identity baseline;
then vary (pos,scale,anchor) ONE at a time and fit the exact Motion transform. Only then fix
buildTransformMatrix. The anchor-scaling bug (238×5.25≈1250 off-frame) stands as the leading cause of
the coverage cap; confirm the exact formula before editing the shared transform code.
Probes: /tmp/mksquare.py, /tmp/mkmask.py, /tmp/stripparent.py, /tmp/hrender.py.

## CLEAN SQUARE PROBE (2026-07-24) — exact discrepancy isolated
Replaced the mask geometry with a sharp 200×200 SQUARE (±100 shape units), feather=0, pos=0 sc=1
anchorY=-238 (the mask's authored anchor), parent 'Transition Diagonal' scale stripped to 1:
  FCP:    centroid (1210, 932)  size 354×322 px
  engine: centroid (1209, 144)  size 282×282 px
FINDINGS (X is CORRECT, Y is the bug):
  - X centroid matches (1210 vs 1209). 
  - Y centroid: FCP 932 vs engine 144 — off by 788px. The engine places the square near the TOP,
    FCP near the BOTTOM. This is the anchorY=-238 being applied with the WRONG SIGN/scale on Y.
  - Size: FCP 354×322 (non-square! wider than tall) vs engine 282×282 (square). FCP applies a
    NON-UNIFORM magnification (~1.77× X, ~1.61× Y) — there's a base coordinate scale (~1.7×,
    project-unit->pixel?) that the engine applies as ~1.4× (282/200) uniformly. The Aspect Ratio=1.5
    param may drive the non-uniform X/Y.
EXACT NEXT STEP: sweep anchorY ∈ {-238,0,+238} and scale ∈ {1,2} on this clean square, record FCP
centroid+size each, and SOLVE the linear map (pixel = A·shapeCoord + b) for X and Y separately.
That yields the exact Motion mask transform (base scale, anchor sign, aspect). Then fix
buildTransformMatrix / the mask raster transform and verify no 65-slug regression.
Harness: /tmp/mksquare.py (square with pos/scale/anchor args), /tmp/hrender.py.
